se mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|year = 2015\n|team = Kentucky Wildcats\n|sport = football\n|logo = Kentucky Wildcats 2005 logo.svg\n|logo_size = 150px\n|logo_alt = Kentucky Wildcats logo\n|conference = Southeastern Conference\n|division = Eastern Division\n|short_conf = SEC\n|CoachRank = \n|APRank = \n|BCSRank = \n|record = 5\u20137\n|conf_record = 2\u20136\n|head_coach = [[Mark Stoops]]\n|hc_year=3rd\n|off_coach =Shannon Dawson\n|oc_year=1st\n|def_coach =[[D. J. Eliot]]\n|dc_year=3rd\n|off_scheme = [[Spread offense|Air Raid]]\n|def_scheme = [[3-4]]\n|stadium = [[Commonwealth Stadium (Kentucky)|Commonwealth Stadium]]<br />(Capacity: 61,000)\n|champion =\n|bowl = \n|bowl_result =  \n}}\n{{2015 SEC football standings}}\n\nThe '''2015 Kentucky Wildcats football team''' (variously \"Kentucky\", \"UK\", or \"Wildcats\") represents the [[University of Kentucky]] in the [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Wildcats compete in its 122nd season and 82nd as a member of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) as part of its [[Southeastern Conference#Current members|Eastern Division]]. The team is led by head coach [[Mark Stoops]], which is his third year coaching the team, and the Wildcats play its home games at [[Commonwealth Stadium (Kentucky)|Commonwealth Stadium]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].\n\nAfter the completion of the [[2014 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2014 season]], the Wildcats signed one of their highest rated [[Recruiting (college athletics)|recruiting class]]es in February.  They completed their spring practice in April.\n\n==Pre-season==\n\n===Previous season===\nIn 2014\u20132015, the Wildcats lost their final six games of the season after starting the season 5\u20131, completing their second year under [[Mark Stoops]] at 5-7 and 2\u20136 in the SEC (6th-East). They lost to in-state rival Louisville 40\u201344 to end the season, missing out on their fourth consecutive bowl game since the 2010\u20132011 season when they lost to Pittsburgh in the BBVA Compass Bowl.\n\n===Fall camp===\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Coaching staff===\n[[List of Kentucky Wildcats head football coaches|Kentucky head coach]] Mark Stoops enters his third year as the Wildcat's head coach for the 2015 season.  During his previous two seasons he led the Wildcats to an overall record of 7 wins and 17 losses.  Despite the losing record, he doubled his win total from his first season to his second.\n\nOn November 30, 2014 Offensive Coordinator [[Neal Brown]] accepted the Head Coach position at [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]], where he was an assistant from 2006 to 2009.<ref name=BrownCJ>{{cite news |title=UK's Neal Brown Announced as Troy Head Coach|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/uk-beat/2014/11/30/uks-neal-brown-announced-as-troy-head-coach/19715995/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=November 30, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=BrownAL>{{cite news |title=Troy Confirms Kentucky Offensive Coordinator Neal Brown Has Accepted Job as Trojans' Next Head Coach|first=Tommy|last=Hicks|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/11/troy_announces_on_twitter_kent.html|newspaper=[[The Birmingham News]]|date=November 30, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>  In his place Kentucky hired [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] Co-offensive Coordinator Shannon Dawson on December 19, 2014.<ref name=DawsonCJ>{{cite news |title=It's Official: Dawson Hired as UK Coordinator|first=Jonathan|last=Lintner|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2014/12/19/official-kentucky-hires-wvus-shannon-dawson-offensive-coordinator/20646773/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=DawsonESPN>{{cite web |title=UK Hires Shannon Dawson as O-Boss|first=Travis|last=Haney|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/12044617/kentucky-wildcats-hire-shannon-dawson-west-virginia-mountaineers-run-offense|work=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=April 10, 2015|date=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSpecial Teams coach Craig Naivar accepted a position  at [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] under his former colleague [[Tom Herman (American football)|Tom Herman]] on December 18, 2014.<ref name=Naivar>{{cite news |title=UK Football Assistant Craig Naivar Leaving|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/uk-beat/2014/12/18/uk-football-assistant-craig-naivar-leaving/20592375/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>  The position he vacated was filled by [[California Golden Bears football|California]] assistant Andy Buh on February 4, 2015.<ref name=Buh>{{cite news |title=UK's Stoops Confirms Buh Hire, Staff Shakeup|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/02/04/uks-stoops-confirms-buh-hire-staff-shakeup/22872861/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>  Stoops announced with Buh's hiring that the special teams would be a joint effort among multiple assistant coaches.<ref name=\"Buh\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#005DAA;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Name</span>\n! style=\"background:#005DAA;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Position</span>\n! style=\"background:#005DAA;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Consecutive season at<br />Kentucky in current position</span>\n|-\n| [[Mark Stoops]] || [[Head coach]] ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Shannon Dawson || [[Offensive Coordinator]], [[Quarterbacks coach|Quarterbacks]] ||align=center| 1st\n|-\n| [[D. J. Eliot]] || [[Defensive Coordinator]],  Inside [[Linebacker]]s ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Derrick Ansley || [[Defensive back]]s ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Jimmy Brumbaugh || [[Defensive line coach|Defensive Line]] ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Andy Buh || Outside linebackers ||align=center| 1st\n|-\n| Tommy Mainord || [[Wide receiver]]s ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Vince Marrow || [[Tight end|Tight End]]s, Recruiting Coordinator ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| John Schlarman || [[Offensive line coach|Offensive Line]] ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Chad Scott || [[Running back]]s ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n| Erik Korem || Strength and Conditioning ||align=center| 3rd\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\"font-size: 8pt\" align=\"center\"|'''Reference:'''\n|}\n\n===Transfers===\nThird string quarterback Maxwell Smith announced on January 11 that he would transfer to [[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State]] for his senior season.<ref name=SmithSD>{{cite news |title=UK Quarterback Maxwell Smith to Transfer|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/01/09/kentucky-quarterback-maxwell-smith-announces-transfer/21532051/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=January 11, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14 running back Braylon Heard announced he would forgo his last season of eligibility and enter his name into the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref name=HeardNFL>{{cite web|title=Braylon Heard Declares for NFL Draft|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011415aaf.html|publisher=University of Kentucky Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416002023/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011415aaf.html#|archive-date=April 16, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=HeardLHL>{{cite news |title=Kentucky Junior Running Back Braylon Heard to Enter NFL Draft|first=Jennifer|last=Smith|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2015/01/14/3641380_q-a-with-new-kentucky-offensive.html?rh=1|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>  Heard rushed for 366 yards and four touchdowns, averaging 5.1 yards per carry in 2014.\n\nOn February 4 running back Josh Clemons announced he will transfer from the program in May after he receives his degree.<ref name=ClemonsTr>{{cite news |title=UK Running Back Josh Clemons to Transfer|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/02/04/uk-running-back-josh-clemons-to-transfer/22851995/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015 signing class===\n{{see also|American football positions|Glossary of American football|Recruiting (college athletics)}}\nPrior to [[National Signing Day]] on February 4, 2015, four players enrolled for the spring semester in order to participate in spring practice<ref name=SDLHL>{{cite news |title=Kentucky Announces Early Enrollees|first=Jennifer|last=Smith|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2015/01/21/3653435/kentucky-announces-early-enrollees.html|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> The early enrollments from high school included offensive lineman George Asafo-Adjei, tight end C.J. Conrad, defensive end Kengera Daniel, and linebacker Jordan Jones.<ref name=\"SDLHL\"/>\n\nOn National Signing Day, Alabama signed 18 additional players out of high school that completed the 2015 recruiting class. The class was highlighted by 2 players from the \"[[ESPN]] 300\": No.&nbsp;214&nbsp;Marcus Walker; and No.&nbsp;244&nbsp;Eli Brown.<ref name=\"ESPN300\">{{cite web |title=ESPNU 300 Class of 2015|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/view/rn300/sort/rank/class/2015|work=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> Kentucky signed a top-35 class according to ''[[Rivals.com]]'', ''[[Scout.com]]'' and ''[[247Sports.com]]''.<ref name=SDCJ>{{cite news |title=UK Rides Roller Coaster, Signs Strong Class|first=Kyle|last=Tucker|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/02/04/kentucky-football-overcomes-late-recruiting-losses-sign-top-class-nationally/22887123/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"LHL15\">{{cite news |title=Late Flurry Elevates UK|first=Ben|last=Roberts|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2015/02/04/3678161/late-flurry-elevates-kentuckys.html|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to those signed as part of the 2015 class, on December 12, 2014 [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] transfers, tight end Greg Hart and linebacker Courtney Love, announced they would enroll and join Kentucky's football team.<ref name=NebTr>{{cite news |title=2 Nebraska Football Players Transferring to UK|first=Steve|last=Jones|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/recruiting/kentucky/2014/12/11/nebraskas-courtney-love-greg-hart-transferring-kentucky-football/20254459/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=December 11, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>  Due to health concerns of relatives, both players plan to apply for hardship waivers that would allow them to play in 2015 without sitting out due to NCAA transfer rules.<ref name=\"NebTr\" />\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=|collapse=yes|year=2015}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit      = [[Josh Allen (linebacker)|Josh Allen]]\n| position     = LB\n| hometown     = [[Montclair, New Jersey]]\n| highschool   = [[Montclair High School (New Jersey)|Montclair]]\n| feet         = 6 \n| inches       = 4\n| weight       = 220\n| 40           = \n| commitdate   = January 31, 2015\n| scout stars  = 3\n| rivals stars = 3\n| 247 stars    = 3\n| espn stars   = 3\n| grayshirt    = \n}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit      = George Asafo-Adjei\n| position     = OL\n| hometown     = [[West Chester Township, Butler County, Ohio|West Chester, Ohio]]\n| highschool  